# ========================================
# REJECTION AND ALTERNATIVES
# ========================================

@reject_proposal
on-arrival: coalition_dissent += 1; economic_minister_party_relation -= 5

We reject the [+ economic_minister_party +]'s proposal. Tensions within the coalition rise.

What should we propose instead?

- @propose_keynesian: Propose deficit-financed public works
- @propose_orthodox: Propose balanced-budget approach
- @propose_middle: Propose moderate compromise

@propose_keynesian
choose-if: (finance_minister_party = "SPD" or chancellor_party = "SPD") and (left_strength >= 30 or neorevisionist_strength >= 25)
unavailable-subtitle: We lack the authority or internal support to override the Economic Minister with radical proposals.
on-arrival: budget -= 3; unemployed -= 4; demand_impulse += 2; coalition_dissent += 2; economic_minister_party_relation -= 10; left_strength += 3; fiscal_stance += 0.8; fiscal_demand += 1; credit_conditions += 0.5
go-to: root

We override the Economic Minister and implement aggressive stimulus: expanded public credit and deficit-financed job creation. Coalition tensions rise sharply.

@propose_orthodox
on-arrival: budget += 0.5; inflation -= 1; unemployed += 1; coalition_dissent += 1; economic_minister_party_relation -= 8; reformist_strength += 2; fiscal_stance -= 0.3; credit_conditions -= 0.3; fiscal_demand -= 0.4
go-to: root

We insist on fiscal orthodoxy with tight credit discipline. The Economic Minister is overruled. Unemployment worsens.

@propose_middle
on-arrival: budget -= 1.5; unemployed -= 2; coalition_dissent += 0.5; economic_minister_party_relation -= 3; fiscal_demand += 0.4; credit_conditions += 0.2
go-to: root

We negotiate a middle path: moderate fiscal expansion with limited credit easing. This satisfies no one fully but keeps the coalition together.
